---
import ToolLayout from '@/components/tools/ToolLayout.astro';
import ToolCta from '@/components/tools/ToolCta.astro';
import HreflangGenerator from '@/components/tools/HreflangGenerator';
import { tools } from '@/data/tools';

const tool = tools.find((t) => t.slug === 'hreflang-generator')!;
---
<ToolLayout tool={tool}>
  <HreflangGenerator client:load />

  <div slot="body" class="prose-page">
    <h2>What hreflang tags do</h2>
    <p>
      <code>hreflang</code> tells Google which language and region each version of a page is for, so
      the right version shows to the right searcher and your translated pages don&rsquo;t compete with
      each other as duplicates. They&rsquo;re essential the moment you ship the same content in more
      than one language or for more than one country.
    </p>

    <h2>The two rules people get wrong</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>They must be reciprocal.</strong> If your English page points to the Spanish page,
        the Spanish page must point back. One-way references are ignored.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Every page lists the whole set — including itself.</strong> Each URL in a language
        group carries the full list of alternates, self-referencing tag included, plus an{' '}
        <code>x-default</code> for unmatched users.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Where to add them in Webflow</h2>
    <p>
      For static pages, paste the tags into Page Settings → Custom Code → inside{' '}
      <code>&lt;head&gt;</code>. For CMS-driven pages, use field bindings in the Collection page&rsquo;s
      head so each item outputs its own set. Webflow&rsquo;s native Localization adds hreflang
      automatically — this generator is for manual setups, Weglot/Linguana edge cases, and
      cross-domain ccTLD structures. The full playbook is in my{' '}
      <a href="/blog/webflow-international-seo/">Webflow international SEO guide</a> and the{' '}
      <a href="/blog/webflow-localization-vs-weglot/">Localization vs Weglot vs Linguana comparison</a>.
    </p>

    <h2>Validate before you ship</h2>
    <p>
      After publishing, confirm the tags resolve and reciprocate with a crawler (Ahrefs, Screaming
      Frog) or Google Search Console&rsquo;s International Targeting report. A single broken return
      tag quietly disables hreflang for the whole cluster.
    </p>

    <ToolCta />
  </div>
</ToolLayout>
